The man behind Dymon’s stellar rise | 








The man behind Dymon’s stellar rise – Dymon Asia
























































 
































About DymonBusinesses  Public Markets    Macro Strategies    Dymon Manager Solutions      Private Markets        Dymon Asia Private Equity        Dymon Asia VenturesNewsroomSupporting our Community  Education  Elderly  YouthContact usInvestor Login
 


















The man behind Dymon’s stellar rise

Friday, January 9, 2015
When Mr Danny Yong started what is now Dymon Asia Macro Fund with US$113 million in 2008, billionaire investor Paul Tudor Jones’ hedge fund company was his first outside backer.
Six years later, Mr Yong’s one-time upstart has grown to US$3.5 billion (S$4.7 billion) in assets and delivered the second-best performance of any large Asia-based hedge fund, Bloomberg Markets magazine will report in its February issue.
From its perch in Singapore, Dymon Asia Macro returned 17 per cent in the first 10 months of last year. Only the Quantedge Global Fund’s 32.3 per cent topped it in Asia in Bloomberg Markets’ annual ranking of funds with US$1 billion or more in assets.
Dymon was also a standout worldwide. It came in at No. 10 among all large funds in a bad year for some macro funds, which seek to profit from trends in currencies, interest rates, and equities and commodities markets.
Managers of big Asia-focused funds can struggle to deliver consistent gains. Markets are smaller and less liquid than those in the US and Europe, and there is a limited pool of talented professionals to run the funds. Mr Yong, 43, who has a resume that includes Goldman Sachs Group, has 18 years of experience trading Asian securities.
Dymon Asia Macro returned 82.1 per cent from August 2008 through last October, according to a source. That compares with a 16 per cent loss for the HFRX Macro/CTA Index, which measures macro hedge funds and the so-called commodity-trading advisers that trade futures and forward contracts on commodities, financial assets and currencies.
The Dymon fund’s only calendar- year loss was for its inaugural five months in 2008.
In 2011, Dymon Asia Macro topped all US$1 billion–plus Asian funds, with a return of more than 20 per cent after fees.
“Dymon, over the years, demonstrated strong risk management,” says Mr Stephane Pizzo, managing partner of Singapore-based Lotus Peak Capital, which invests in hedge funds. “This allows them to limit losses during quiet months, while fully participating when the move finally happens.”
Dymon Asia Macro took advantage of the lull in major market moves during the first half of last year, says Mr David Chan, chief executive of Dymon Asia Capital (Singapore), the management firm that oversees US$4.4 billion of assets, including the macro fund.
He says the fund bought cheap options to benefit from trends it expected to crystallise in later months. One of the most profitable bets was on China’s yuan. The currency had dropped 3 per cent against the US dollar in trading outside China in the first four months.
Mr Yong says he expected the yuan would rebound and finish the year roughly where it started. Dymon bought call options, which gave it the right to buy the yuan at a specified price during a specified period. The currency strengthened 2 per cent from April to the end of October in trading outside of China.
“Since the global financial crisis, market cycles have shortened and trends are often interspersed with violent corrections that make holding on to long-term positions more challenging,” says Mr Yong, who is also chief investment officer of Dymon Asia Capital. “Using options has allowed us to structure trades with compelling risk-reward profiles and allows us to generate superior returns when we call the market right.”
The US Federal Reserve handed hedge funds last year’s most anticipated trading catalyst. The central bank announced in late October that it would end the asset buying that underpinned its third round of quantitative easing. The Fed’s purchases were designed to boost economic growth and investor confidence.
Unlike some peers who bet Treasury bond prices would decline as a result, Mr Yong sought to gain from a stronger US economy by going long on the US dollar against the Japanese yen.
The strategy had two benefits: It shielded Dymon investors from the largest one-day decline since 2009 in US Treasury yields on Oct 15, a drop that reversed in the following days. It also allowed Dymon to profit from additional stimulus moves and pension reforms Mr Yong says he expected would lead Japan’s currency lower.
Dymon boosted the size of its bet against the yen, convinced the Japanese economy was running out of steam. From Aug 13, the day the second-quarter gross domestic product (GDP) number was announced, through Oct 31, the US dollar strengthened 9.7 per cent against Japan’s currency. It had extended the gain by a further 6.6 per cent as of the end of last month, after the Bank of Japan decided to expand the stimulus in late October. On Nov 17, the country announced it had slipped back into recession in the third quarter.
Mr Yong has lived through plenty of Asia’s turmoil in a 20-year career. He joined what is now JPMorgan Chase & Co as a trader on the Asian markets-derivatives and fixed-income desk in 1997, just months before the region’s financial crisis.
He moved to Goldman Sachs’ Hong Kong derivatives trading desk in 2000, then spent 2 1/2 years with the firm in Japan. In 2005, Citadel hired him to set up and run Asian currencies, interest-rates, relative-value and macro trading in Hong Kong for the Chicago-based firm.
BLOOMBERG
Source: The Straits Times © Singapore Press Holdings Limited. Permission required for reproduction.
